Walton is not about to dash anyone's illusions. Folksy was an understatement. At the end of the day, Sam Walton's heritage is in the shopping malls, not the bookstores. Or they will find it dreary and downbeat. Given the pleadings of publishers - Doubleday paid about Dollars 4m for the manuscript - and a rather natural desire to have a final say, he can hardly be blamed for agreeing to write it. Readers will either find his autobiography lashed with 'good ol common-sense and a lot of harmless, if charming, anecdotes. Oh, come on Sam, is that the whole story. 50. 